  ### `isConstruct` <a name="isConstruct" id="cdktf.App.isConstruct"></a>
  
  ```typescript
  import { App } from 'cdktf'
  
  App.isConstruct(x: any)
  ```
  
  Checks if `x` is a construct.
  
  Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
  instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.
  
  Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
  disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
  consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
  is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
  `instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
  like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
  use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
  library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
  unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
  this type-testing method instead.
  
  #### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="cdktf.App.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>
  
  - *Type:* any
  
  Any object.
  
  ---

  # CloudBackend <a name="CloudBackend" id="cdktf.CloudBackend"></a>
  
  The Cloud Backend synthesizes a {@link https://www.terraform.io/cli/cloud/settings#the-cloud-block cloud block}. The cloud block is a nested block within the top-level terraform settings block. It specifies which Terraform Cloud workspaces to use for the current working directory. The cloud block only affects Terraform CLI's behavior. When Terraform Cloud uses a configuration that contains a cloud block - for example, when a workspace is configured to use a VCS provider directly - it ignores the block and behaves according to its own workspace settings.
  
  ## Initializers <a name="Initializers" id="cdktf.CloudBackend.Initializer"></a>
  

  ### `isConstruct` <a name="isConstruct" id="cdktf.CloudBackend.isConstruct"></a>
  
  ```typescript
  import { CloudBackend } from 'cdktf'
  
  CloudBackend.isConstruct(x: any)
  ```
  
  Checks if `x` is a construct.
  
  Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
  instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.
  
  Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
  disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
  consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
  is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
  `instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
  like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
  use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
  library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
  unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
  this type-testing method instead.
  
  #### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="cdktf.CloudBackend.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>
  
  - *Type:* any
  
  Any object.
  
  ---
  
  ### `isBackend` <a name="isBackend" id="cdktf.CloudBackend.isBackend"></a>

  ```typescript
  import { CloudBackend } from 'cdktf'
  
  CloudBackend.isBackend(x: any)
  ```
  
  #### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="cdktf.CloudBackend.isBackend.parameter.x"></a>
  
  - *Type:* any

  `instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
  like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
  use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
  library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
  unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
  this type-testing method instead.

  ### `isConstruct` <a name="isConstruct" id="cdktf.DataTerraformRemoteState.isConstruct"></a>
  
  ```typescript
  import { DataTerraformRemoteState } from 'cdktf'
  
  DataTerraformRemoteState.isConstruct(x: any)
  ```
  
  Checks if `x` is a construct.
  
  Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
  instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.
  
  Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
  disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
  consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
  is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
  `instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
  like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
  use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
  library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
  unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
  this type-testing method instead.
  
  #### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="cdktf.DataTerraformRemoteState.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>
  
  - *Type:* any
  
  Any object.

  ## Static Functions <a name="Static Functions" id="Static Functions"></a>
  
  | **Name** | **Description** |

  ---
  
  ### `isConstruct` <a name="isConstruct" id="cdktf.DataTerraformRemoteStateAzurerm.isConstruct"></a>
  
  ```typescript
  import { DataTerraformRemoteStateAzurerm } from 'cdktf'
  
  DataTerraformRemoteStateAzurerm.isConstruct(x: any)
  ```
  
  Checks if `x` is a construct.
  
  Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
  instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.
  
  Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
  disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
  consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
  is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
  `instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
  like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
  use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
  library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
  unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
  this type-testing method instead.
  
  #### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="cdktf.DataTerraformRemoteStateAzurerm.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>
  
  - *Type:* any
  
  Any object.
  
  ---

  ## Static Functions <a name="Static Functions" id="Static Functions"></a>
  
  | **Name** | **Description** |

  ---
  
  ### `isConstruct` <a name="isConstruct" id="cdktf.DataTerraformRemoteStateCos.isConstruct"></a>
  
  ```typescript
  import { DataTerraformRemoteStateCos } from 'cdktf'
  
  DataTerraformRemoteStateCos.isConstruct(x: any)
  ```
  
  Checks if `x` is a construct.
  
  Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
  instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.
  
  Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
  disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
  consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
  is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
  `instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
  like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
  use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
  library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
  unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
  this type-testing method instead.
  
  #### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="cdktf.DataTerraformRemoteStateCos.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>
  
  - *Type:* any
  
  Any object.
  
  ---

  ## Static Functions <a name="Static Functions" id="Static Functions"></a>
  
  | **Name** | **Description** |

  | <code><a href="#cdktf.DataTerraformRemoteStateEtcdV3.isConstruct">isConstruct</a></code> | Checks if `x` is a construct. |
  
  ---
  
  ### `isConstruct` <a name="isConstruct" id="cdktf.DataTerraformRemoteStateEtcdV3.isConstruct"></a>
  
  ```typescript
  import { DataTerraformRemoteStateEtcdV3 } from 'cdktf'
  
  DataTerraformRemoteStateEtcdV3.isConstruct(x: any)
  ```
  
  Checks if `x` is a construct.
  
  Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
  instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.
  
  Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
  disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
  consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
  is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
  `instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
  like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
  use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
  library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
  unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
  this type-testing method instead.
  
  #### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="cdktf.DataTerraformRemoteStateEtcdV3.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>
  
  - *Type:* any
  
  Any object.
  
  ---

  ---
  
  ### `isConstruct` <a name="isConstruct" id="cdktf.DataTerraformRemoteStateHttp.isConstruct"></a>
  
  ```typescript
  import { DataTerraformRemoteStateHttp } from 'cdktf'
  
  DataTerraformRemoteStateHttp.isConstruct(x: any)
  ```
  
  Checks if `x` is a construct.
  
  Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
  instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.
  
  Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
  disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
  consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
  is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
  `instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
  like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
  use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
  library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
  unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
  this type-testing method instead.
  
  #### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="cdktf.DataTerraformRemoteStateHttp.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>
  
  - *Type:* any
  
  Any object.
  
  ---

  ## Static Functions <a name="Static Functions" id="Static Functions"></a>
  
  | **Name** | **Description** |

  ---
  
  ### `isConstruct` <a name="isConstruct" id="cdktf.DataTerraformRemoteStateOss.isConstruct"></a>
  
  ```typescript
  import { DataTerraformRemoteStateOss } from 'cdktf'
  
  DataTerraformRemoteStateOss.isConstruct(x: any)
  ```
  
  Checks if `x` is a construct.
  
  Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
  instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.
  
  Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
  disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
  consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
  is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
  `instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
  like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
  use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
  library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
  unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
  this type-testing method instead.
  
  #### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="cdktf.DataTerraformRemoteStateOss.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>
  
  - *Type:* any
  
  Any object.
  
  ---

  ## Static Functions <a name="Static Functions" id="Static Functions"></a>
  
  | **Name** | **Description** |

  ---
  
  ### `isConstruct` <a name="isConstruct" id="cdktf.DataTerraformRemoteStateS3.isConstruct"></a>
  
  ```typescript
  import { DataTerraformRemoteStateS3 } from 'cdktf'
  
  DataTerraformRemoteStateS3.isConstruct(x: any)
  ```
  
  Checks if `x` is a construct.
  
  Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
  instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.
  
  Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
  disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
  consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
  is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
  `instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
  like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
  use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
  library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
  unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
  this type-testing method instead.
  
  #### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="cdktf.DataTerraformRemoteStateS3.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>
  
  - *Type:* any
  
  Any object.
  
  ---

  ### `isConstruct` <a name="isConstruct" id="cdktf.EtcdBackend.isConstruct"></a>
  
  ```typescript
  import { EtcdBackend } from 'cdktf'
  
  EtcdBackend.isConstruct(x: any)
  ```
  
  Checks if `x` is a construct.
  
  Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
  instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.
  
  Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
  disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
  consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
  is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
  `instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
  like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
  use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
  library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
  unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
  this type-testing method instead.
  
  #### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="cdktf.EtcdBackend.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>
  
  - *Type:* any
  
  Any object.
  
  ---
  
  ### `isBackend` <a name="isBackend" id="cdktf.EtcdBackend.isBackend"></a>
  
  ```typescript
  import { EtcdBackend } from 'cdktf'
  
  EtcdBackend.isBackend(x: any)
  ```
  
  #### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="cdktf.EtcdBackend.isBackend.parameter.x"></a>
  
  - *Type:* any

  ### `isConstruct` <a name="isConstruct" id="cdktf.HttpBackend.isConstruct"></a>
  
  ```typescript
  import { HttpBackend } from 'cdktf'
  
  HttpBackend.isConstruct(x: any)
  ```
  
  Checks if `x` is a construct.
  
  Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
  instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.
  
  Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
  disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
  consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
  is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
  `instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
  like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
  use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
  library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
  unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
  this type-testing method instead.
  
  #### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="cdktf.HttpBackend.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>
  
  - *Type:* any
  
  Any object.
  
  ---
  
  ### `isBackend` <a name="isBackend" id="cdktf.HttpBackend.isBackend"></a>
  
  ```typescript
  import { HttpBackend } from 'cdktf'
  
  HttpBackend.isBackend(x: any)
  ```
  
  #### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="cdktf.HttpBackend.isBackend.parameter.x"></a>
  
  - *Type:* any

  ### `isConstruct` <a name="isConstruct" id="cdktf.OssBackend.isConstruct"></a>
  
  ```typescript
  import { OssBackend } from 'cdktf'
  
  OssBackend.isConstruct(x: any)
  ```
  
  Checks if `x` is a construct.
  
  Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
  instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.
  
  Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
  disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
  consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
  is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
  `instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
  like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
  use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
  library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
  unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
  this type-testing method instead.
  
  #### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="cdktf.OssBackend.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>
  
  - *Type:* any
  
  Any object.
  
  ---
  
  ### `isBackend` <a name="isBackend" id="cdktf.OssBackend.isBackend"></a>
  
  ```typescript
  import { OssBackend } from 'cdktf'
  
  OssBackend.isBackend(x: any)
  ```
  
  #### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="cdktf.OssBackend.isBackend.parameter.x"></a>
  
  - *Type:* any

  ---
  
  ### `isConstruct` <a name="isConstruct" id="cdktf.RemoteBackend.isConstruct"></a>
  
  ```typescript
  import { RemoteBackend } from 'cdktf'
  
  RemoteBackend.isConstruct(x: any)
  ```
  
  Checks if `x` is a construct.
  
  Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
  instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.
  
  Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
  disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
  consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
  is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
  `instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
  like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
  use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
  library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
  unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
  this type-testing method instead.
  
  #### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="cdktf.RemoteBackend.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>
  
  - *Type:* any
  
  Any object.
  
  ---
  
  ### `isBackend` <a name="isBackend" id="cdktf.RemoteBackend.isBackend"></a>

  ## Static Functions <a name="Static Functions" id="Static Functions"></a>
  
  | **Name** | **Description** |
  | --- | --- |
  | <code><a href="#cdktf.TerraformAsset.isConstruct">isConstruct</a></code> | Checks if `x` is a construct. |
  
  ---
  
  ### `isConstruct` <a name="isConstruct" id="cdktf.TerraformAsset.isConstruct"></a>
  
  ```typescript
  import { TerraformAsset } from 'cdktf'
  
  TerraformAsset.isConstruct(x: any)
  ```
  
  Checks if `x` is a construct.
  
  Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
  instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.
  
  Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
  disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
  consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
  is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
  `instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
  like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
  use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
  library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
  unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
  this type-testing method instead.
  
  #### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="cdktf.TerraformAsset.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>
  
  - *Type:* any
  
  Any object.
  
  ---
  
  ## Properties <a name="Properties" id="Properties"></a>
  
  | **Name** | **Type** | **Description** |
  | --- | --- | --- |
  | <code><a href="#cdktf.TerraformAsset.property.node">node</a></code> | <code>constructs.Node</code> | The tree node. |
  | <code><a href="#cdktf.TerraformAsset.property.fileName">fileName</a></code> | <code>string</code> | Name of the asset. |
  | <code><a href="#cdktf.TerraformAsset.property.path">path</a></code> | <code>string</code> | The path relative to the root of the terraform directory in posix format Use this property to reference the asset. |
  | <code><a href="#cdktf.TerraformAsset.property.assetHash">assetHash</a></code> | <code>string</code> | *No description.* |

  ## Static Functions <a name="Static Functions" id="Static Functions"></a>
  
  | **Name** | **Description** |
  | --- | --- |
  | <code><a href="#cdktf.TerraformDataSource.isConstruct">isConstruct</a></code> | Checks if `x` is a construct. |
  
  ---
  
  ### `isConstruct` <a name="isConstruct" id="cdktf.TerraformDataSource.isConstruct"></a>
  
  ```typescript
  import { TerraformDataSource } from 'cdktf'
  
  TerraformDataSource.isConstruct(x: any)
  ```
  
  Checks if `x` is a construct.
  
  Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
  instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.
  
  Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
  disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
  consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
  is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
  `instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
  like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
  use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
  library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
  unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
  this type-testing method instead.
  
  #### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="cdktf.TerraformDataSource.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>
  
  - *Type:* any
  
  Any object.
  
  ---

  ## Static Functions <a name="Static Functions" id="Static Functions"></a>
  
  | **Name** | **Description** |
  | --- | --- |
  | <code><a href="#cdktf.TerraformHclModule.isConstruct">isConstruct</a></code> | Checks if `x` is a construct. |
  
  ---
  
  ### `isConstruct` <a name="isConstruct" id="cdktf.TerraformHclModule.isConstruct"></a>
  
  ```typescript
  import { TerraformHclModule } from 'cdktf'
  
  TerraformHclModule.isConstruct(x: any)
  ```
  
  Checks if `x` is a construct.
  
  Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
  instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.
  
  Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
  disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
  consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
  is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
  `instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
  like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
  use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
  library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
  unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
  this type-testing method instead.
  
  #### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="cdktf.TerraformHclModule.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>
  
  - *Type:* any
  
  Any object.
  
  ---

  ### `isConstruct` <a name="isConstruct" id="cdktf.TerraformOutput.isConstruct"></a>
  
  ```typescript
  import { TerraformOutput } from 'cdktf'
  
  TerraformOutput.isConstruct(x: any)
  ```
  
  Checks if `x` is a construct.
  
  Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
  instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.
  
  Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
  disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
  consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
  is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
  `instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
  like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
  use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
  library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
  unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
  this type-testing method instead.
  
  #### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="cdktf.TerraformOutput.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>
  
  - *Type:* any
  
  Any object.
  
  ---
  
  ### `isTerrafromOutput` <a name="isTerrafromOutput" id="cdktf.TerraformOutput.isTerrafromOutput"></a>

  ## Static Functions <a name="Static Functions" id="Static Functions"></a>

  ---
  
  ### `isConstruct` <a name="isConstruct" id="cdktf.TerraformRemoteState.isConstruct"></a>
  
  ```typescript
  import { TerraformRemoteState } from 'cdktf'
  
  TerraformRemoteState.isConstruct(x: any)
  ```
  
  Checks if `x` is a construct.
  
  Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
  instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.
  
  Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
  disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
  consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
  is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
  `instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
  like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
  use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
  library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
  unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
  this type-testing method instead.
  
  #### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="cdktf.TerraformRemoteState.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>
  
  - *Type:* any
  
  Any object.
  
  ---

  ### `isConstruct` <a name="isConstruct" id="cdktf.TerraformStack.isConstruct"></a>
  
  ```typescript
  import { TerraformStack } from 'cdktf'
  
  TerraformStack.isConstruct(x: any)
  ```
  
  Checks if `x` is a construct.
  
  Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
  instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.
  
  Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
  disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
  consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
  is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
  `instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
  like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
  use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
  library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
  unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
  this type-testing method instead.
  
  #### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="cdktf.TerraformStack.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>
  
  - *Type:* any
  
  Any object.
  
  ---
  
  ### `isStack` <a name="isStack" id="cdktf.TerraformStack.isStack"></a>
  
  ```typescript
  import { TerraformStack } from 'cdktf'
  
  TerraformStack.isStack(x: any)
  ```
  
  #### `x`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="x" id="cdktf.TerraformStack.isStack.parameter.x"></a>
  
  - *Type:* any
